ARCHITECTURE:
{{ architecture }}

Rules:
- Every subtask has a `type`, exactly one of: "scaffold", "implement",
  "integrate", "config", "install".
- `test_command` is REQUIRED for implement and integrate subtasks: a single
  concrete shell command runnable from the project root (e.g.
  "pytest tests/test_notes.py -q"). Optional for other types.
- `files` lists the actual FILES (with extensions) the subtask creates or
  edits — never a bare directory. Every subtask lists at least one file.
- `dependencies` lists subtask ids that must be done first. Order subtasks so
  dependencies always come earlier. No cycles.
- `intent` is one sentence: what this subtask accomplishes.
- `role` is exactly one of: backend, frontend, database, infrastructure,
  testing, review — whichever domain this subtask's files/work primarily
  belong to. If a subtask spans multiple domains (e.g. a full-stack feature),
  pick the PRIMARY role and note the secondary domain in `intent`.
- Keep the breakdown COARSE: a handful of substantial subtasks beats many
  trivial ones. Directories are created implicitly by writing files.
- Use names that are VALID identifiers for the language (Python packages use
  underscores, never hyphens).
- Every status starts as "pending". Use ids like T001, T001.1, T001.2, T002.

Output ONLY a single JSON object (no prose, no code fences) with this schema:

{
  "project": "<name>",
  "tasks": [
    {
      "id": "T001",
      "title": "...",
      "goal": "...",
      "status": "pending",
      "subtasks": [
        {
          "id": "T001.1",
          "title": "...",
          "type": "scaffold",
          "intent": "one sentence: what this accomplishes",
          "role": "infrastructure",
          "files": ["path/one.py", "path/two.py"],
          "dependencies": [],
          "test_command": "pytest -q",
          "status": "pending"
        }
      ]
    }
  ]
}
